WEBVTT

00:02.670 --> 00:06.839
"The Profit"...
a New York fashion designer
was once a phenomenal success...

00:06.907 --> 00:08.741
What's the biggest year
that you've had?

00:08.809 --> 00:10.075
SUSANA: 13 million.

00:10.144 --> 00:12.945
LEMONIS: ...but today, she finds
herself under siege.

00:13.014 --> 00:14.913
SUSANA: There's no respect here
for me at all.

00:14.982 --> 00:16.648
There's no respect.
Where's the respect?

00:16.717 --> 00:18.717
LEMONIS: Customers
are deserting her label.

00:18.786 --> 00:21.954
ANNA: Honestly, we didn't
make any money since 2009.

00:22.023 --> 00:23.922
LEMONIS: Friends and family
are demanding

00:23.991 --> 00:25.591
a piece of her business.

00:25.659 --> 00:27.593
SUSANA: The brothers think
I owe them their birth right.

00:27.661 --> 00:28.594
LEMONIS: I feel like
you're being kind of,

00:28.662 --> 00:29.795
like, shaken down.

00:29.864 --> 00:31.663
And instead of standing
up for herself

00:31.732 --> 00:33.465
and fighting for her brand,

00:33.534 --> 00:35.801
she's letting it fall
apart at the seams.

00:35.870 --> 00:37.903
SUSANA: This is bull[BLEEP]
It's total bull[BLEEP]

00:37.972 --> 00:41.073
LEMONIS: If I can't
help her regain confidence

00:41.142 --> 00:43.609
and harness
her incredible talent...

00:43.677 --> 00:45.244
SUSANA: It's really
stressful to...

00:45.312 --> 00:48.113
LEMONIS:
...Susana Monaco's best days

00:48.182 --> 00:49.681
will be behind her.

00:49.750 --> 00:51.683
My name is Marcus Lemonis,

00:51.752 --> 00:53.385
and I risk my own money

00:53.454 --> 00:55.521
to save struggling businesses.

00:55.589 --> 00:57.423
We're not going to wake up
every morning wondering

00:57.491 --> 00:58.724
if we have a job.

00:58.793 --> 01:00.259
We're going to wake up
every morning wondering

01:00.327 --> 01:01.660
how many jobs
we have to do.

01:01.729 --> 01:03.629
It's not always pretty.

01:03.697 --> 01:06.131
Everything's going to change.
Everything.

01:06.200 --> 01:08.233
But I do it to save jobs,

01:08.302 --> 01:10.102
and I do it to make money.

01:10.171 --> 01:11.437
This...
Let's go to work.

01:11.505 --> 01:13.939
...is "The Profit."

01:18.312 --> 01:22.681
In 1996, Susana Monaco
launched her namesake label,

01:22.750 --> 01:25.751
a collection of women's
apparel marked by clean

01:25.820 --> 01:27.453
and contemporary designs.

01:27.521 --> 01:30.255
SUSANA: The front is
narrower than the back.

01:30.324 --> 01:32.558
LEMONIS: She had grown up
working at her family's

01:32.626 --> 01:34.026
cut-and-sew factory

01:34.095 --> 01:37.129
and then engaged them
to help her with manufacturing.

01:37.198 --> 01:40.566
Before long, she was
in thousands of retailers

01:40.634 --> 01:44.103
across the country with revenue
exceeding $10 million.

01:44.171 --> 01:45.771
ANNA: This is
the best-selling for holiday.

01:45.840 --> 01:46.939
They love it.

01:47.007 --> 01:48.207
LEMONIS:
But the Great Recession

01:48.275 --> 01:51.043
dealt the label a severe blow,

01:51.112 --> 01:53.946
and Susana has been unable
to reverse the damage.

01:54.014 --> 01:55.214
SUSANA: Stay in business
or not stay in business...

01:55.282 --> 01:56.748
that's the choice.

01:56.817 --> 02:00.119
LEMONIS: Today, sales are off
more than 50% from their peak.

02:00.187 --> 02:01.386
SUSANA: This is devastating.

02:01.455 --> 02:04.656
LEMONIS: And the company
is bleeding money.

02:04.725 --> 02:07.426
I'm looking to grow
my fashion business,

02:07.495 --> 02:09.527
and despite Susana's troubles,

02:09.597 --> 02:11.930
I'm impressed by the success
she's had in the past.

02:11.999 --> 02:14.299
If I can help get
the brand back on track,

02:14.368 --> 02:17.703
I'm confident she can have
an even brighter future.

02:19.273 --> 02:20.339
ANNA: Hi.
LEMONIS: Hi.

02:20.407 --> 02:21.273
ANNA: How are you?
LEMONIS: How are you?

02:21.342 --> 02:22.608
I'm Marcus.
ANNA: Anna.

02:22.676 --> 02:23.709
LEMONIS: Nice to meet you, Anna.
ANNA: Nice to meet you.

02:23.777 --> 02:25.811
LEMONIS:
Is this the showroom?

02:25.880 --> 02:27.212
ANNA:
Yes, please come in.

02:27.281 --> 02:29.214
LEMONIS: Okay.

02:29.283 --> 02:31.150
ANNA: Marcus,
this is Susana.

02:31.218 --> 02:32.151
LEMONIS: Oh, hi, Susana.

02:32.219 --> 02:33.252
SUSANA: Hi.
LEMONIS: Marcus.

02:33.320 --> 02:34.386
SUSANA: Hi, Marcus.
Nice to meet you.

02:34.455 --> 02:35.721
LEMONIS: How are you?
Nice to meet you.

02:35.789 --> 02:38.490
SUSANA: Yeah.
LEMONIS: Don't be nervous.

02:38.559 --> 02:40.292
You guys manufacture
your own stuff?

02:40.361 --> 02:41.527
ANNA: Yes.
SUSANA: Yes.

02:41.595 --> 02:43.362
ANNA: We manufacture
in our New Jersey factory.

02:43.430 --> 02:44.863
Sue is responsible for design,

02:44.932 --> 02:47.166
and I'm responsible
for all operations and sales.

02:47.234 --> 02:49.101
LEMONIS: So you handle
production and sales?

02:49.170 --> 02:51.737
ANNA: Yes.
I'm very capable.

02:51.805 --> 02:53.071
LEMONIS:
That's interesting.

02:53.140 --> 02:55.841
SUSANA: The front stuff
is too emotional for me.

02:55.910 --> 02:57.609
ANNA: Sue is the creative
engine of the company.

02:57.678 --> 02:58.577
SUSANA: Yeah.
ANNA: So we don't want

02:58.646 --> 03:00.179
to expose her to all the...

03:00.247 --> 03:01.947
you know,
all the unpleasant stuff.

03:02.016 --> 03:04.216
SUSANA: I don't like to be
in the front of things.

03:04.285 --> 03:05.417
LEMONIS: Okay.

03:05.486 --> 03:07.452
SUSANA: I like to be
in my world working.

03:07.521 --> 03:09.721
LEMONIS: You're the artist.
SUSANA: Yes. I just...

03:09.790 --> 03:12.424
ANNA: She's very... takes
everything very close to heart.

03:12.493 --> 03:14.459
And, you know, in operations,
every day there is a problem.

03:14.528 --> 03:16.028
There is... I mean,
every second there is a problem.

03:16.096 --> 03:19.031
Not every day...
every five minutes.

03:19.099 --> 03:21.633
LEMONIS: Right away I noticed
this very interesting dynamic

03:21.702 --> 03:23.869
between the two of them.
Anna's the employee,

03:23.938 --> 03:25.938
but she's dominating
the conversation,

03:26.006 --> 03:29.007
and Susana, who's the owner
who has her name on the door,

03:29.076 --> 03:31.343
she's standing there
like a bystander.

03:31.412 --> 03:32.978
Why don't we look
at the product?

03:33.047 --> 03:36.081
SUSANA: Okay.
LEMONIS: Let's do that.

03:36.150 --> 03:37.382
What's the demo?

03:37.451 --> 03:38.951
SUSANA: I would say
that it's a cross section.

03:39.019 --> 03:40.652
There's the young girl in there.
There's a middle girl.

03:40.721 --> 03:43.422
There's a working girl.
There's a lot of girls in there.

03:43.490 --> 03:45.624
LEMONIS: Is that code for saying
it's all over the place?

03:45.693 --> 03:48.660
SUSANA: Um, maybe.

03:48.729 --> 03:50.062
LEMONIS: Look,
you would expect a company

03:50.130 --> 03:51.697
like this to have a core lineup,

03:51.765 --> 03:54.666
a clear direction on exactly
what they were selling,

03:54.735 --> 03:56.868
and there would be
some consistency to it.

03:56.937 --> 03:58.403
Who's your customer for this?

03:58.472 --> 04:00.072
ANNA: Well this is
a young doll.

04:00.140 --> 04:01.440
SUSANA: 20s, 30s.

04:01.508 --> 04:02.841
ANNA: 20s, not even 30s.

04:02.910 --> 04:04.743
LEMONIS: But when you look
at her lineup here,

04:04.812 --> 04:05.911
it's all over the place.

04:05.980 --> 04:07.879
There's a dress
made of this material

04:07.948 --> 04:09.548
and pants made of that material,

04:09.617 --> 04:13.318
and there's no story
to the lineup, no collection.

04:13.387 --> 04:16.088
I'll tell you what's
interesting about this rack.

04:16.156 --> 04:18.656
This is a very easy
crossover to somebody

04:18.726 --> 04:20.392
who likes to live
in athleisure wear.

04:20.461 --> 04:21.560
SUSANA: Yes.
ANNA: Yes.

04:21.629 --> 04:23.295
This is supplex,
which is our base fabric.

04:23.364 --> 04:25.597
LEMONIS: Okay. That's
how Susana started the company.

04:25.666 --> 04:27.833
LEMONIS: It has
a spandex feel to it.

04:27.901 --> 04:29.201
So it helps people
with shape and curves.

04:29.270 --> 04:30.636
SUSANA: Shape is great.

04:30.704 --> 04:33.238
LEMONIS: But that's a very
different fabric than this.

04:33.307 --> 04:34.973
'Cause this is not supplex.

04:35.042 --> 04:36.808
What's the problem?
SUSANA: It's a little dry.

04:36.877 --> 04:39.044
The economy crashed,
our price point changed,

04:39.113 --> 04:40.712
so we had to work accordingly.

04:40.781 --> 04:42.414
ANNA: Supplex fabric
is unaffordable.

04:42.483 --> 04:44.683
SUSANA: The supplex
is almost $10 a yard.

04:44.752 --> 04:45.951
That's the kicker.

04:46.020 --> 04:47.586
LEMONIS: So this fabric
is how much a yard?

04:47.655 --> 04:48.687
BOTH: About $4.

04:48.756 --> 04:50.122
LEMONIS: What are
the overall margins?

04:50.190 --> 04:51.857
SUSANA: The overall margin
of the company is...

04:51.925 --> 04:54.526
you know, not great.
It's in the 40s.

04:54.595 --> 04:56.261
LEMONIS: In a business
like this, your margin

04:56.330 --> 04:58.864
should be no less than 50%.

04:58.932 --> 05:00.332
And what's even more surprising

05:00.401 --> 05:02.000
is they should be
even higher,

05:02.069 --> 05:04.936
considering that they're using
low-quality materials.

05:05.005 --> 05:07.139
What it really tells me
is that there has

05:07.207 --> 05:09.641
to be terrible inefficiencies
in their process

05:09.710 --> 05:11.843
that I'll have
to look out for.

05:11.912 --> 05:15.013
ANNA: Okay, so this
is the pattern-making area.

05:15.082 --> 05:17.582
Everything is done
on the computer, all patterns.

05:17.651 --> 05:19.551
LEMONIS: And you're
literally making to order.

05:19.620 --> 05:21.086
SUSANA: Yes.
LEMONIS: Sell an order,

05:21.155 --> 05:22.788
cut, sew it,
and ship it.

05:22.856 --> 05:24.222
SUSANA: Yes.

05:24.291 --> 05:26.491
LEMONIS: And so, when it goes
to the cut and sew shop,

05:26.560 --> 05:27.726
they work off this pattern.

05:27.795 --> 05:30.028
SUSANA: Yes.
My dad's manufacturing plant.

05:30.097 --> 05:31.730
LEMONIS: Oh, you're
at your dad's building.

05:31.799 --> 05:32.931
SUSANA: Yes.

05:33.000 --> 05:35.534
LEMONIS: So you're paying
your dad rent.

05:35.602 --> 05:36.735
SUSANA: Yes.

05:36.804 --> 05:38.170
LEMONIS: So I should think
about the factory

05:38.238 --> 05:39.237
as a shared building...

05:39.306 --> 05:40.539
SUSANA: Yes.

05:40.607 --> 05:42.207
LEMONIS: ...where your employees
make your clothes.

05:42.276 --> 05:44.710
SUSANA: Yes.
LEMONIS: ...and his employees

05:44.778 --> 05:46.778
do third-party manufacturing
for other people?

05:46.847 --> 05:48.080
SUSANA: Yes.
LEMONIS: How often do you...

05:48.148 --> 05:50.282
How much time
do you spend there?

05:50.351 --> 05:52.818
SUSANA: I don't spend
any time there.

05:52.886 --> 05:54.052
LEMONIS: You don't
go see what...

05:54.121 --> 05:55.153
You don't inspect
what's happening?

05:55.222 --> 05:58.056
SUSANA: No.
I used to, um, go, not...

05:58.125 --> 06:00.125
LEMONIS: When's the last time
you were there?

06:00.194 --> 06:01.360
SUSANA: The last time...
LEMONIS: Last week?

06:01.428 --> 06:02.694
SUSANA: No. No. No.
ANNA: No.

06:02.763 --> 06:03.895
LEMONIS: Last month?
SUSANA: I would say, months.

06:03.964 --> 06:05.464
LEMONIS: Do you go, Anna?
ANNA: I don't go.

06:05.532 --> 06:07.699
They don't like us.

06:07.768 --> 06:09.101
LEMONIS:
Your employees don't like you?

06:09.169 --> 06:11.703
ANNA: Her brothers.

06:11.772 --> 06:12.838
LEMONIS: What do the brothers

06:12.906 --> 06:13.972
have to do
with your dad's building?

06:14.041 --> 06:15.073
SUSANA:
They're running the factory.

06:15.142 --> 06:16.441
ANNA: They're running
the factory.

06:16.510 --> 06:18.744
LEMONIS: So you have
no interaction with the people

06:18.812 --> 06:20.612
that actually make your clothes?

06:20.681 --> 06:23.081
SUSANA: Yes, no contact.

06:23.150 --> 06:25.984
LEMONIS: So this is a business
relationship, contract labor,

06:26.053 --> 06:27.919
where you're paying
for all the employees

06:27.988 --> 06:29.855
and all the work that's done.

06:29.923 --> 06:32.991
That's your only source
of manufacturing the products.

06:33.060 --> 06:35.327
But Susana never actually
goes to the factory

06:35.396 --> 06:37.195
that she pays
the employees in?

06:37.264 --> 06:40.031
Because she's got some
problem with her family?

06:40.100 --> 06:41.600
I'm gonna spend
a few minutes with Susana

06:41.668 --> 06:43.168
so I can get to know her.
ANNA: Yes. Mm-hmm.

06:43.237 --> 06:44.703
LEMONIS: Why did you
get into this business?

06:44.772 --> 06:46.037
SUSANA: I was born
in this business.

06:46.106 --> 06:47.038
LEMONIS: You were how?

06:47.107 --> 06:48.940
SUSANA: My dad moved here
from Italy

06:49.009 --> 06:51.176
in the late '50s, early '60s.

06:51.245 --> 06:53.812
He started manufacturing
clothing.

06:53.881 --> 06:55.947
I grew up in that factory.

06:56.016 --> 06:57.482
Worked there through
high school.

06:57.551 --> 06:59.418
I did the designs.
LEMONIS: And he manufactured.

06:59.486 --> 07:00.585
SUSANA: He manufactured.

07:00.654 --> 07:02.053
LEMONIS: And then what
do you do next?

07:02.122 --> 07:03.688
SUSANA: I worked with a few
really great companies.

07:03.757 --> 07:06.925
Mm, didn't really feel...

07:06.994 --> 07:09.494
I don't know, fulfilled enough,
so I created the collection

07:09.563 --> 07:11.329
and it was going
incredibly well.

07:11.398 --> 07:13.432
LEMONIS: What's the biggest year
that you've had?

07:13.500 --> 07:16.435
SUSANA: $13 million,
then my father decides

07:16.503 --> 07:18.570
that I should split
the stock of my company

07:18.639 --> 07:20.572
with my brothers equally.
LEMONIS: Why?

07:20.641 --> 07:23.909
SUSANA:
Because he wants his family

07:23.977 --> 07:26.144
to be secure in life.

07:26.213 --> 07:27.979
This is old-school way
of doing things,

07:28.048 --> 07:29.314
'cause all of my...

07:29.383 --> 07:30.382
LEMONIS: Okay, hold on a second.
SUSANA: Yeah. Yeah.

07:30.451 --> 07:32.217
LEMONIS:
He walks up and says,

07:32.286 --> 07:34.286
"I know you started
this business by yourself,

07:34.354 --> 07:35.787
you're doing amazing,

07:35.856 --> 07:38.757
and I want you to take
two-thirds of the business

07:38.826 --> 07:40.125
and I want you
to give it away."

07:40.194 --> 07:41.593
SUSANA: Yes.
LEMONIS: To your brothers?

07:41.662 --> 07:42.727
SUSANA: Yes.

07:42.796 --> 07:44.062
LEMONIS: Who are not
in the business?

07:44.131 --> 07:46.031
SUSANA: They're actually
working at the factory.

07:46.099 --> 07:48.433
LEMONIS: And so their payroll
is coming from your production.

07:48.502 --> 07:50.702
SUSANA: Yes. Yes.
Paying them a salary.

07:50.771 --> 07:52.838
LEMONIS: And did your brothers
put any money in your company?

07:52.906 --> 07:54.473
SUSANA: No.

07:54.541 --> 07:58.210
It's not fine, but...

07:58.278 --> 08:00.278
LEMONIS: So, I feel like
you're being kind of,

08:00.347 --> 08:02.781
like, shaken down.

08:06.553 --> 08:08.520
Anna, what's your biggest worry?

08:08.589 --> 08:11.389
ANNA: The problem here is that
we afraid that the brothers,

08:11.458 --> 08:13.158
they're gonna screw us,
you know?

08:13.227 --> 08:14.993
Because we don't trust them
at all

08:15.062 --> 08:17.829
because they think that they
deserve stock in the company,

08:17.898 --> 08:19.130
that this is
their birth right.

08:19.199 --> 08:20.165
LEMONIS: They deserve
in stock in the factory.

08:20.234 --> 08:21.967
ANNA: No, in Susana Monaco.

08:22.035 --> 08:23.235
LEMONIS: Why would
they deserve stock here?

08:23.303 --> 08:25.136
ANNA: Well, good question.

08:25.205 --> 08:26.338
LEMONIS: Now,
are you with partners

08:26.406 --> 08:28.306
with Susana in this business?
ANNA: No.

08:28.375 --> 08:31.042
And the thing is that
it's really upsetting me,

08:31.111 --> 08:32.811
because I think
it should be 50/50

08:32.880 --> 08:36.114
because I carry a lot of stuff.

08:36.183 --> 08:37.315
LEMONIS: You get paid
as well or no?

08:37.384 --> 08:38.549
ANNA: Yes.

08:38.619 --> 08:40.184
LEMONIS: You do get paid.
ANNA: Yes.

08:40.254 --> 08:41.253
LEMONIS: Similar to what
Susana makes?

08:41.321 --> 08:42.520
ANNA: No, I'm paid more.

08:42.589 --> 08:44.422
Her salary is $100,000.

08:44.491 --> 08:45.690
My salary is $175,000.

08:45.759 --> 08:47.759
I feel why should I cut
my salary

08:47.828 --> 08:49.060
when I'm doing all the work,

08:49.129 --> 08:50.462
and I don't have
partnership papers?

08:50.531 --> 08:51.763
And I said that
to her straight out.

08:51.832 --> 08:54.266
I said, "It's one thing
if I have 50/50."

08:54.334 --> 08:57.402
But now, I... I mean,
technically, I'm an employee.

08:57.471 --> 09:01.039
LEMONIS: So Anna either gets
twice as much as Susana makes

09:01.108 --> 09:03.542
or she gets half the company?

09:03.610 --> 09:05.911
It feels like Susana is
being run into the ground

09:05.979 --> 09:07.178
all over the place.

09:07.247 --> 09:09.347
Her family wants
a piece of the business.

09:09.416 --> 09:11.716
Her employees want
a piece of the business.

09:11.785 --> 09:13.051
It's ridiculous.

09:13.120 --> 09:15.987
What's your biggest concern
about the business?

09:16.056 --> 09:17.989
ANNA: Well, biggest concern
is, of course,

09:18.058 --> 09:19.558
we're not making money.

09:19.626 --> 09:22.727
I mean, honestly we didn't make
any money since 2009, so...

09:22.796 --> 09:24.095
LEMONIS: No money.
ANNA: Yes.

09:24.164 --> 09:26.031
There's no cash flow
in the company.

09:26.099 --> 09:28.400
So what happens
is we ship in the world,

09:28.468 --> 09:30.468
we ship in the world,
there is no cash,

09:30.537 --> 09:32.237
so this is super stressful.

09:34.741 --> 09:37.175
LEMONIS: So, you know, when I
met with Anna individually,

09:37.244 --> 09:40.278
she told me she thought she
should own 50% of the company.

09:40.347 --> 09:41.680
SUSANA: Yes.

09:41.748 --> 09:44.549
She's making a lot
of decisions here.

09:44.618 --> 09:47.852
I'm not, you know, the pit bull.

09:47.921 --> 09:49.921
She's the pit bull.

09:49.990 --> 09:51.590
I need a pit bull.
LEMONIS: Yeah, but your pit bull

09:51.658 --> 09:53.325
isn't supposed to bite you.
SUSANA: No.

09:53.393 --> 09:55.894
LEMONIS: They're supposed
to protect you.

09:55.963 --> 09:57.629
SUSANA: Yeah, but...
LEMONIS: The purpose of a person

09:57.698 --> 09:59.264
like that is
to protect you and...

09:59.333 --> 10:01.399
SUSANA: Yes, but she does
in every other sense.

10:01.468 --> 10:02.968
It's not about bullying,
it's about...

10:03.036 --> 10:04.269
LEMONIS: But I feel like you're
giving me a rationalization...

10:04.338 --> 10:05.704
SUSANA: I'm not rationalizing,
it's the reason.

10:05.772 --> 10:07.038
LEMONIS: ...of why you let her
behave that way, though.

10:07.107 --> 10:09.207
Even when we're talking,
she always talks over you.

10:09.276 --> 10:10.542
She's not gonna take
a cut in pay

10:10.611 --> 10:12.177
and she wants 50%
of the business.

